		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Tue, Aug 22nd 12:03 PM2000 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/db/classes.html?class=14&mid=96664463517221&num=8&post=1&replyto=9669602095065"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=9669602095065></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=798"><span id=>DarcMT</span></a><b><span id=></span></b><br />7 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Default [2.00]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=DarcMT&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Bah..you don't need all those spells hotkeyed! I am really frustrated at people that hotkey a Melee attack key.&nbsp;&nbsp;Why waste that spot when you can assign it a keyboard command??  Move attack from A to something else.  You can do this by the options/keyboard screen in game.  My set up is Q=attack, W=con, E=nearest NPC.  They are conveniently close together and easy to remember after some time playing with it. You don't need two lifetaps memorized either, unless you are at a new lifetap spell lvl and your new one fizzles a lot.  For lvls 1-16, my hot keys looked like this:<br><br>1. Lifetap<br>2. Pet attack<br>3. Pet back off<br>4. Assist<br>5. Poison bolt or Heat blood<br>6. Spells<br><br>Reasons:  You always want to hotkey a lifetap.  Lifetap will keep you alive in dire instances and you don't want to fumble around with using the mouse to select the spell.  Pet attack and back off should always be memorized, if not on the first 6 slots, then on the second set.  You will need pet back off later in life when in dungeons, so get used to it now.  If you don't have pet back off hotkeyed later on, you are going to be causing a lot of trains and people will not want you in their groups.  Assist is a definate must.  Early on, it helps to assist your pet if you get jumped by more than one mob.  You have to fight the same mob your pet is fighting for efficiency.  Later lvls you will be assisting the main tank when he pulls mutiple mobs.  This helps out enchanters tremendously with crowd control.  It makes no sense to mez a mob when some pet is whacking on it.  I hotkey one of my non-snare spells as well.  You will almost always lead off with a darkness spell when soloing, so you really don't care about using the mouse for that, but its nice having a hotkey for your second DoT.  Having spells hotkeyed is a given considering you will be using that button to mediate.<br><br>Once you acquire Feign Death at 16, your hotkey slot should change.  You will want to hotkey it so you again won't have to delay your reaction by using a mouse to click it.  If you are in trouble and need to FD, pressing a button is a lot easier than scrolling your cursor over to the spell gem and pressing it.  For my case, I replaced my number 5 hotkey with FD and it looks like this:<br><br>1. Lifetap<br>2. Pet attack<br>3. Pet back off<br>4. Assist<br>5. Feign death<br>6. Spells<br><br>If you want you may hotkey your DoT's on your second set of hotkeys, but I never did.  When fear kiting and using DoT's, once I landed the darkness and fear, I just laid on the DoT's by mouse.  Once I reached lvl 35 and could med while sitting, my hotkey slot 6 became Sit.  Spells went to second set of hotkeys.<br><br>I hope this helps someone.  I have played 5 necromancers within the past year, so I speak from experience.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >2 Replies</td></tr></table>
